{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6e8ce202-b8d9-4cfa-8963-d28ec237aa7f","content":"A `NullReferenceException` after startup is not a CLR activation issue — it's a runtime bug in your application code. CLR activation logs only cover the shim/loader phase (picking and loading the correct .NET Framework runtime), not application-level exceptions.\n\n**CLR activation logs won't help here.** They'd be useful if:\n- The wrong runtime version was loaded\n- The runtime failed to load at all\n- A .NET 3.5 Feature-on-Demand dialog appeared unexpectedly\n\n**For your NullReferenceException, try these instead:**\n1. **Check the stack trace** — it tells you exactly which line dereferenced `null`.\n2. **Enable first-chance exception debugging** in Visual Studio (Debug → Exceptions → check CLR Exceptions).\n3. **Collect a crash dump** — use `dotnet-dump collect` or set `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1`.\n4. **Add logging** around the startup path to identify which object is `null`.\n\nWould you like help with any of these approaches — for example, collecting a crash dump or setting up dump analysis?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f04873e2-c6b3-4eda-b212-c1ccbddf4908","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\" This seems relevant to the user's request about analyzing CLR activation logs.\n\nLet me invoke that skill.","outputTokens":385,"requestId":"7855:2E7316:1DDDF19:214D602:69FA9B31"},"id":"1587e9bf-6802-438b-88f0-6d9bf2efafd1","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:37:00.200Z","parentId":"f38d23f8-24f3-4431-92c9-f61a995daa85"}
